# Fucntion to create dictionary from pickle file
def creating_dict(caption_list):
    caption_dict = dict()
    for i in caption_list:
        temp=i.split("\t")
        img_name, img_caption = temp[0][:-2], temp[1]
        temp2=img_name.split(".")
        img_name=temp2[0]
        
        # Create dictionary
        if img_name not in caption_dict:
            caption_dict[img_name] = list()
        caption_dict[img_name].append(img_caption)
    return(caption_dict)

Image caption preprocessing:

The below function is for the following purposes:

*) Making sure all the words in each of the sentences are converted to a lower case to avoid duplication.
*) Removing words with a length of less than two --> removing single letters and punctuations
In [12]:
def cleaning(data):
    dict_2 = dict()
    for key, value in data.items():
        for i in range(len(value)):
            lines = ""
            line1 = value[i]
            for j in line1.split():
                if len(j) < 2:
                    continue
                j = j.lower()
                lines += j + " "
            if key not in dict_2:
                dict_2[key] = list()
            
            dict_2[key].append(lines)
            
    return dict_2

#saving all the preprocessing done above to a text file for further purposes.
def creating_text(data2, filename):
    lines = list()
    for key, value in data2.items():
        for desc in value:
            lines.append(key + ' ' + desc)
    data = '\n'.join(lines)
    file = open(filename, 'w')
    file.write(data)
    file.close()

creating_text(data2, 'captions.txt')

In [17]:
images = 'dataset/images/'
img = glob(images + '*.jpg')
print(len(img))

def preprocess(image_path):
    # Convert all the images to size 224*224 as expected by the resnet50 model
    img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(image_path, target_size=(224, 224))
    # Convert PIL image to numpy array of 3-dimensions
    x = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img)
    # Add one more dimension
    x = np.expand_dims(x, axis=0)
    # pre-process the images using preprocess_input() from resnet module
    x = tf.keras.applications.resnet50.preprocess_input(x)
    return x

# Function to encode a given image into a vector of size (2048, )
def encode(image):
    image = preprocess(image) # preprocess the image
    fea_vec = model.predict(image) # Get the encoding vector for the image
    fea_vec = np.reshape(fea_vec, fea_vec.shape[1]) # reshape from (1, 2048) to (2048, )
    return fea_vec

# convert descriptons(cleaned) dictionary to list of descriptions
def to_lines(descriptions):
    all_desc = list()
    for key in descriptions.keys():
        [all_desc.append(d) for d in descriptions[key]]
    return all_desc

# calculate the length of the description with the most words
def max_length(descriptions):
    lines = to_lines(descriptions)
    return max(len(d.split()) for d in lines)

# determine the maximum sequence length
max_length = max_length(data2)
print('Description Length: %d' % max_length)

Description Length: 29

Creating the data generator:

Each image is converted into its respective feature length, and all the descriptions are padded so that it has to be passed through an LSTM network for future word prediciton.

In [24]:
# data generator
def data_generator(descriptions, photos, wordtoix, max_length, num_photos_per_batch):
    X1, X2, y = list(), list(), list()
    n=0
    # loop for ever over images
    while 1:
        for key, desc_list in descriptions.items():
            n+=1
            if key =="2258277193_586949ec62":
                print(key)
                continue
            # retrieve the photo feature
            photo = photos[key+'.jpg']
            for desc in desc_list:
                # encode the sequence
                seq = [wordtoix[word] for word in desc.split(' ') if word in wordtoix]
                # split one sequence into multiple X, y pairs
                for i in range(1, len(seq)):
                    # split into input and output pair
                    in_seq, out_seq = seq[:i], seq[i]
                    # pad input sequence
                    in_seq = pad_sequences([in_seq], maxlen=max_length)[0]
                    # encode output sequence
                    out_seq = to_categorical([out_seq], num_classes=vocab_size)[0]
                    # store
                    X1.append(photo)
                    X2.append(in_seq)
                    y.append(out_seq)
            # yield the batch data
            if n==num_photos_per_batch:
                yield ([array(X1), array(X2)], array(y))
                X1, X2, y = list(), list(), list()
                n=0

Creating word embedding vectors for each unique word for a fixed length is done using pre-trained glove.6B.200d.txt . The word embedding method is used to map every single index of words to a 200 length vector to make it an uniformly sized distribution. The following code block does the above:

NB: For the below code to work "glove.6B.200d.txt" should be downloaded and loaded from https://github.com/stanfordnlp/GloVe¶

In [25]:
embeddings_index = {}
f = open('glove.6B.200d.txt', encoding="utf-8")

for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()
print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

embedding_dim = 200

# Get 200-dim dense vector for each of the 10000 words in our vocabulary
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((vocab_size, embedding_dim))

for word, i in wordtoix.items():
    #if i < max_words:
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # Words not found in the embedding index will be all zeros,
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        
embedding_matrix.shape

As per the requirements mentioned in the question model is created and trained,

*) 5 layered LSTM layers are used.
*) L1 regularizarion is applied to all layers
*) Dropout is added to avoid overfitting.

The image vector and the LSTM predictions are combined as one unit. This is passed through some dense layers and then to a SoftMax activation function, which is equivalent to the size of the pre-defined vocabulary.

In [26]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Input, Conv2D, MaxPool2D, LSTM, add
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Activation, Dropout, Flatten, Embedding
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from keras.regularizers import l1

inputs1 = Input(shape=(2048,))
fe1 = Dropout(0.4)(inputs1)
fe2 = Dense(256, activation='relu')(fe1)

inputs2 = Input(shape=(max_length,))
se1 = Embedding(vocab_size, embedding_dim, mask_zero=True)(inputs2)
se2 = LSTM(12,return_sequences=True,recurrent_regularizer=l1(0.05))(se1)
se3 = LSTM(24,return_sequences=True,recurrent_regularizer=l1(0.05))(se2)
se4 = LSTM(48,return_sequences=True,recurrent_regularizer=l1(0.05))(se3)
se5 = LSTM(128,return_sequences=True,recurrent_regularizer=l1(0.05))(se4)
se6 = Dropout(0.4)(se5)
se7 = LSTM(256,recurrent_regularizer=l1(0.05))(se6)

decoder1 = add([fe2, se7])
decoder2 = Dense(1000, activation='relu')(decoder1)
outputs = Dense(vocab_size, activation='softmax')(decoder2)

model = Model(inputs=[inputs1, inputs2], outputs=outputs)

#printing model summary
model.summary()

Reasons for choosing adam as optimizer

It adds to the advantages of Adadelta and RMSprop, the storing of an exponentially decaying average of past gradients similar to momentum.

*) Adam is the best among the adaptive optimizers in most of the cases.
*) Good with sparse data: the adaptive learning rate is perfect for this type of datasets.
*) There is no need to focus on the learning rate value. hence default learning rate of ADAM is used
In [29]:
model.layers[1].set_weights([embedding_matrix])
model.layers[1].trainable = False

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam')
#Running for 10 epochs
epochs = 10
number_pics_per_bath = 3
steps = len(data2)//number_pics_per_bath

features = pickle.load(open("images1.pkl", "rb"))
tf.config.run_functions_eagerly(True)
t1_start=process_time()
#Model is saved after each epoch to save valuable training time and also incase of overfitting
generator = data_generator(data2, features, wordtoix, max_length, number_pics_per_bath)
history=model.fit(generator, epochs=epochs, steps_per_epoch=steps,verbose=1)
t1_stop=process_time()
model.save('model_final.h5')

In [36]:
def predicting_the_caption(picture):
    in_text = 'startseq'
    for i in range(max_length):
        sequence = [words_to_index[w] for w in in_text.split() if w in words_to_index]
        sequence = pad_sequences([sequence], maxlen=29)
        yhat = model.predict([picture,sequence], verbose=0)
        yhat = np.argmax(yhat)
        word = index_to_words[yhat]
        in_text += ' ' + word
        if word == 'endseq':
            break
    final = in_text.split()
    final = final[1:-1]
    final = ' '.join(final)
    return final
